Clustering Analysis with Mall Customers Dataset¶

1. Introduction¶

In this notebook, we will use the Mall Customers Dataset from Kaggle to demonstrate how to apply several unsupervised learning methods. The main objectives are:

  1. Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) and feature engineering.
  2. Compare different clustering algorithms (e.g., K-means, Hierarchical Clustering, DBSCAN).
  3. Provide insights into the results and discuss potential business or practical applications.

2. Data Overview¶

We use the Mall Customers dataset, which contains information about customer ID, gender, age, annual income, and spending score.

Dataset columns:¶

  • CustomerID: Unique Customer ID
  • Genre: Gender (Male/Female)
  • Age: Age of the customer
  • Annual Income (k$): Annual Income in thousands of dollars
  • Spending Score (1-100): An indicator (1–100) of how much they spend

The goal is to cluster the customers based on these characteristics.

4. Clustering Methods¶

We'll apply three clustering algorithms:

  • K-Means
  • Hierarchical Clustering
  • DBSCAN

Then we'll compare the results using metrics like the Elbow Method, Silhouette Score, and visual inspection.

4.1 K-means Clustering¶

  1. Use the Elbow Method to determine a good candidate for the number of clusters (k).
  2. Validate with Silhouette Scores.
  3. Assign cluster labels and visualize via PCA.
In [78]:
# 4.1.1 Elbow Method
sse = []
k_range = range(1, 10)

for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.plot(k_range, sse, marker="o")
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("SSE (Inertia)")
plt.title("Elbow Method")
plt.show()
In [79]:
# 4.1.2 Silhouette Scores
sil_scores = []
k_candidates = range(2, 10)  # Silhouette cannot be computed for k=1

for k in k_candidates:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)
    sil = silhouette_score(X_scaled, labels)
    sil_scores.append(sil)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.plot(k_candidates, sil_scores, marker="o")
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.title("Silhouette Scores by k")
plt.show()

best_k = k_candidates[np.argmax(sil_scores)]
print("Best k based on Silhouette Score:", best_k)

Best k based on Silhouette Score: 6
In [80]:
# 4.1.3 K-means with best_k
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=best_k, random_state=42)
cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

df["Cluster_Kmeans"] = cluster_labels  # attach cluster labels to original df

# 2D Visualization: use PCA for dimensionality reduction
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)
df["pca1"] = X_pca[:, 0]
df["pca2"] = X_pca[:, 1]

plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="pca1", 
    y="pca2", 
    hue="Cluster_Kmeans",
    palette="Set2"
)
plt.title(f"K-means Clusters (k={best_k})")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

4.2 Hierarchical Clustering¶

We'll perform Hierarchical Clustering using linkage and then select clusters by cutting the dendrogram at a chosen distance.

In [81]:
# 4.2.1 Dendrogram
Z = linkage(X_scaled, method='ward')
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
dendrogram(Z)
plt.title("Dendrogram (Ward Linkage)")
plt.xlabel("Data points")
plt.ylabel("Distance")
plt.show()
In [82]:
# 4.2.2 Cut the dendrogram
max_d = 10  # Example threshold; choose based on the dendrogram
clusters_hc = fcluster(Z, max_d, criterion='distance')
df["Cluster_HC"] = clusters_hc

n_clusters_hc = len(np.unique(clusters_hc))
print("Number of clusters (Hierarchical):", n_clusters_hc)

# Plot with PCA components
plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="pca1", 
    y="pca2", 
    hue="Cluster_HC",
    palette="Set1"
)
plt.title("Hierarchical Clustering")
plt.show()

Number of clusters (Hierarchical): 4

4.3 DBSCAN¶

DBSCAN requires careful tuning of parameters such as eps and min_samples. It's also sensitive to data scale.

Below is a quick test with a default set of parameters, and then we show how multiple eps values can affect the outcome.

In [83]:
# Example DBSCAN
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.8, min_samples=5)
labels_db = dbscan.fit_predict(X_scaled)

df["Cluster_DBSCAN"] = labels_db
unique_labels = np.unique(labels_db)
print("DBSCAN cluster labels:", unique_labels)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="pca1", 
    y="pca2", 
    hue="Cluster_DBSCAN",
    palette="Set2"
)
plt.title("DBSCAN Clustering")
plt.show()

DBSCAN cluster labels: [-1  0]

4.3.1 DBSCAN Parameter Tuning¶

We can try multiple values of eps to see how the number of clusters (and outliers) changes.

In [84]:
eps_values = [0.5, 0.7, 0.9, 1.1, 1.3]
min_samples = 5

print("DBSCAN Parameter Tuning Results:")
for eps_val in eps_values:
    dbscan_test = DBSCAN(eps=eps_val, min_samples=min_samples)
    labels_test = dbscan_test.fit_predict(X_scaled)
    n_clusters_test = len(set(labels_test)) - (1 if -1 in labels_test else 0)
    n_outliers_test = (labels_test == -1).sum()
    print(f" eps = {eps_val}, #Clusters = {n_clusters_test}, Outliers = {n_outliers_test}")

DBSCAN Parameter Tuning Results:
 eps = 0.5, #Clusters = 6, Outliers = 60
 eps = 0.7, #Clusters = 1, Outliers = 14
 eps = 0.9, #Clusters = 1, Outliers = 3
 eps = 1.1, #Clusters = 1, Outliers = 0
 eps = 1.3, #Clusters = 1, Outliers = 0

5. Comparison and Discussion¶

K-means:

  • Chosen number of clusters: best_k
  • Consider SSE (Elbow) and Silhouette Score.

Hierarchical Clustering:

  • Method: Ward, complete, average, etc.
  • Number of clusters determined by dendrogram threshold or maxclust.

DBSCAN:

  • Parameters: eps, min_samples
  • Number of clusters (excluding noise points) can vary significantly.

Analyze the results, cluster sizes, and potential outliers. You can create additional plots or tables to highlight cluster characteristics.

6. Extended Conclusion and Insights¶

  1. K-means highlighted best_k clusters as optimal. The silhouette score indicated that k = best_k yields relatively distinct groups.
  2. Hierarchical Clustering, when cutting the dendrogram at max_d = 10, suggested n_clusters_hc clusters. By experimenting with different cut thresholds, we get slightly different partitions. One can also check the silhouette scores for various cluster cuts.
  3. DBSCAN depends heavily on eps and min_samples. Smaller eps values often yield more outliers and more clusters, while larger eps values may group many points into a single cluster. In our initial test, most data were grouped into one cluster or marked as noise. By tuning eps, we can potentially discover more meaningful cluster structures.
  4. For each clustering method, analyzing cluster distributions (mean Age, Income, Spending Score) reveals customer segments that could inform marketing or product strategies. For instance, clusters with high Annual Income and high Spending Score might be a key target for premium promotions.
  5. Limitations: We only have three major features (Age, Annual Income, Spending Score). Real-world scenarios could benefit from additional features (e.g., loyalty points, purchase frequency, online/offline channels).
  6. Future Work:
    • Integrate more domain-specific data.
    • Automate hyperparameter searches for DBSCAN.
    • Validate these clusters against real business metrics or domain knowledge.
